The method that most effectively handles **multi-view consistency during stylization** is **Ref-NPR**, and the underlying mathematical reasoning that supports this effectiveness lies in its **reference-based approach** and **semantic correspondence** 
mechanisms.

---

### **1. Overview of the Methods**

- **ARF (Artistic Radiance Fields)**: Uses **Nearest Neighbor Feature Matching (NNFM)** to match features between the rendered view and the style image. It focuses on transferring style details while maintaining content consistency. However, it relies on 
**global feature matching** and may struggle with **occluded regions** and **semantic alignment** across different viewpoints.

- **ReGS (Reference-based Gaussian Splatting Stylization)**: Uses **texture-guided control** to adaptively adjust local Gaussians in 3D Gaussian Splatting (3DGS) to match the style reference. It focuses on **texture fidelity** and **geometric consistency** 
through **depth-based regularization** and **structured densification**. It is effective in **real-time stylization** but may not fully address **semantic alignment** across views.

- **Ref-NPR (Reference-Based Non-Photorealistic Radiance Fields)**: Combines **ray registration**, **semantic feature matching**, and **content-style correspondence** to ensure that the stylized appearance is **consistent across multiple views**. It uses 
**content-aligned reference images** and **semantic feature matching** to ensure that the stylized appearance is **semantically consistent** and **geometrically aligned** with the reference.

---

### **2. Why Ref-NPR is Most Effective for Multi-View Consistency**

#### **2.1. Reference-Based Stylization with Semantic Alignment**

Ref-NPR introduces a **reference-based approach** that ensures **semantic consistency** across views. It uses a **content-aligned reference image** and **semantic feature matching** to ensure that the stylized appearance is **aligned with the reference** in 
both **content** and **style**.

- **Semantic Feature Matching**: Ref-NPR uses **content-style correspondence** to ensure that the stylized appearance is **semantically consistent** with the reference. This is achieved by matching **high-level semantic features** between the content and style
reference using a **content-style mapping**.

- **Mathematical Foundation**: The semantic feature matching is based on **cosine distance** between feature maps extracted from a **pre-trained VGG network**. This ensures that the **semantic structure** of the stylized scene is **aligned with the 
reference**, even across different viewpoints.

  $$
  \text{dist}(F_{\text{content}}, F_{\text{style}}) = 1 - \frac{F_{\text{content}} \cdot F_{\text{style}}}{\|F_{\text{content}}\| \cdot \|F_{\text{style}}\|}
  $$

  This ensures that the **semantic structure** of the stylized scene is **aligned with the reference**, even when the **viewpoint changes**.

#### **2.2. Ray Registration and Depth-Based Regularization**

Ref-NPR uses **ray registration** to project the **style reference** into the **3D scene**. This ensures that the **style is propagated consistently** across different views.

- **Ray Registration**: Ref-NPR uses **depth-based ray registration** to align the **style reference** with the **3D scene**. This ensures that the **style is applied consistently** across different viewpoints.

- **Depth-Based Regularization**: Ref-NPR uses **depth-based regularization** to preserve the **original geometry** of the scene. This ensures that the **stylized appearance** is **geometrically consistent** with the original scene, even when the **viewpoint 
changes**.

  $$
  L_{\text{depth}} = \sum_{i} \|D_i^{\text{stylized}} - D_i^{\text{original}}\|_1
  $$

  This ensures that the **depth structure** of the scene is **preserved**, which is crucial for **multi-view consistency**.

#### **2.3. Template-Based Correspondence Matching (TCM)**

Ref-NPR introduces a **template-based correspondence matching (TCM)** module that ensures that the **style is applied consistently** across different views.

- **TCM**: This module ensures that the **style is applied consistently** across different views by matching **semantic features** between the **content and style reference**.

- **Mathematical Foundation**: TCM uses **semantic feature matching** to ensure that the **style is applied consistently** across different views. This is done by matching **high-level semantic features** between the **content and style reference**.

  $$
  F_{\text{guidance}} = F_{\text{style}}^{\text{matched}}
  $$

  This ensures that the **style is applied consistently** across different views, even when the **viewpoint changes**.

---

### **3. Comparison with ARF and ReGS**

- **ARF**: Uses **NNFM** to match features between the rendered view and the style image. While effective for **style transfer**, it may not ensure **semantic consistency** across different views.

- **ReGS**: Uses **texture-guided control** to adaptively adjust **local Gaussians** in 3DGS. While effective for **real-time stylization**, it may not ensure **semantic consistency** across different views.

- **Ref-NPR**: Combines **ray registration**, **semantic feature matching**, and **depth-based regularization** to ensure **semantic and geometric consistency** across different views. This makes it the **most effective** method for **multi-view consistency** 
during stylization.

---

### **4. Conclusion**

**Ref-NPR** is the most effective method for **multi-view consistency during stylization** due to its **reference-based approach**, **semantic feature matching**, and **depth-based regularization**. These mechanisms ensure that the **stylized appearance** is 
**semantically consistent** and **geometrically aligned** with the **reference**, even when the **viewpoint changes**.

The **mathematical reasoning** behind this effectiveness lies in the use of **cosine distance** for **semantic feature matching**, **depth-based regularization** for **geometric consistency**, and **ray registration** for **style propagation** across different
views. These components work together to ensure that the **stylized appearance** is **consistent across multiple views**, making Ref-NPR the **most effective** method for **multi-view consistency** in 3D scene stylization.
